<h1 id="there-are-several-scenarios-in-which-concurrency-can-occur">There are several scenarios in which concurrency can occur:</h1>

<p>Asynchronyâ€” This means that your program performs non-blocking operations. For example, it can initiate a request for a remote resource via HTTP and then go on to do some other task while it waits for the response to be received. Itâ€™s a bit like when you send an email and then go on with your life without waiting for a response.</p>

<p>Parallelismâ€” This means that your program leverages the hardware of multi-core machines to execute tasks at the same time by breaking up work into tasks, each of which is executed on a separate core. Itâ€™s a bit like singing in the shower: youâ€™re actually doing two things at exactly the same time.</p>

<p>Multithreadingâ€” This is a software implementation allowing different threads to be executed concurrently. A multithreaded program appears to be doing several things at the same time even when itâ€™s running on a single-core machine. This is a bit like chatting with different people through various IM windows; although youâ€™re actually switching back and forth, the net result is that youâ€™re having multiple conversations at the same time.</p>

